Recall that an exponent of  

• 1/2 means “take the principal (positive) square root”, and  
• 1/3 means “take the cube root”.

a) 81^{1/2}  
√81 = 9

b) 125^{1/3}  
∛125 = 5

c) 64^{1/2}  
√64 = 8

Write an n-th root as a power with exponent 1/n, then apply the power-of-a-power rule (multiply exponents).

a.  √[5]{u²}=u^{2/5}

b.  ( √[3]{6x} )⁵ = [(6x)^{1/3}]⁵ = (6x)^{5/3}

c.  √[4]{ (18a / 5b)⁷ } = [(18a / 5b)⁷]^{1/4} = (18a / 5b)^{7/4}

Thus the expressions written with rational exponents are  
a) u^{2/5}, b) (6x)^{5/3}, c) (18a / 5b)^{7/4}.

Use the rules of exponents (valid for positive bases):

• Product: a^m · a^n = a^{m+n}  
• Power of a power: (a^m)^n = a^{mn}  
• Quotient: a^m / a^n = a^{m−n}  

a) y^{1/2} · y^{3/4} = y^{1/2+3/4} = y^{2/4+3/4} = y^{5/4}

b) (x^{12})^{2/3} = x^{12·(2/3)} = x^{24/3} = x^8

c) m^{5/8} / m^{13/8} = m^{5/8−13/8} = m^{−8/8} = m^{−1} = 1/m

Answers:  
a) y^{5/4} b) x^8 c) 1/m

Because the variables are positive we can use the usual rules for rational exponents:

Rule:  (x^m)^n = x^{m·n}

a) (27 q^{3/2})^{4/3}

  • Numerical factor: 27^{4/3} = (27^{1/3})^4 = 3^4 = 81  
  • Variable factor:  q^{(3/2)(4/3)} = q^{2}

Result: 81 q²

b) (a^{1/3} b^{2/3})^{3/2}

  • a–factor:  a^{(1/3)(3/2)} = a^{1/2}  
  • b–factor:  b^{(2/3)(3/2)} = b^{1}

Result: a^{1/2} b  (= b√a)

Answers:

a) 81 q²  
b) b√a (or a^{1/2} b)
